from datetime import timedelta

data['polo_time_0'] = pd.DatetimeIndex(data['polo_time_0']).tz_localize('US/Central') #.tz_convert('US/Central')
data['polo_time_1'] = pd.DatetimeIndex(data['polo_time_1']).tz_localize('US/Central') #.tz_convert('US/Central')

data['gdax_time_ETHUSD'] = pd.DatetimeIndex(data['gdax_time_ETHUSD']).tz_localize('UTC').tz_convert('US/Central')
data['gdax_time_BTCUSD'] = pd.DatetimeIndex(data['gdax_time_BTCUSD']).tz_localize('UTC').tz_convert('US/Central')

Calculate Time Delta in seconds between the 3 pairs, and their various combinations

Let's use polo_time_1 for BTCETH

Note...the time stamp for Poloniex is not the trade time, but rather the time my system made the call to the API (before and after). I have still not located the way to get the timestamp of the market data in the API call

In future, it might make sense to manually watch the exchange while also making API calls to help determine how much latency we are dealing with. This will also help when the project shifts to executing trades.

All calculations will subtract the API call made first in the script from the API call made subsequently

The chart above shows the pricing of two markets coming from the same API (GDAX). So it is safe to assume that the API is providing the last trade for each currency pair, and we can ffill the data. The order book has probably changed during this time, but there are not likely any new trades in the currency pair that is lagging in terms of it's timestamp relative tot he currency pair with the newer timestamp.

For our strategy analysis initially, we will try to filter for when trades coming from the GDAX API are within a certain range of seconds from each other.

Conclusion

It will be easy enough to ffill the data from the two currencies streaming from the GDAX API, but the timestamp of trades coming from the Poloniex API is captured locally, which is a challenge. As noted before, it is probably neccesary to monitor both brokerages for market movements that may have occurred in real time, but were not reported by the most recent API call.

Using most recent trade data at all times, determine if and when Triangle Arbitrage opportunities existed in this data set.

dollar_investment = 1000
### BUY BTCUSD from GDAX ######
data['BTCUSD_Value'] = dollar_investment / data['BTCUSD_PRICE'] # Provides Ownership of BTC
#data['BTCUSD_Value'] = data['BTCUSD_PRICE'] * data['BTCUSD_Units_Owned']
#################################

### Sell BTCETH from Poloniex #####
#data['EURGBP_Value'] = data['EURUSD_Value']*data['EURGBP_Bid'] # MARKET TAKER ## #REFERENCE CODE
#data['BTCETH_Units_Sold'] = data['BTCUSD_Units_Owned'] / data['BTCETH_PRICE']
#data['BTCETH_VALUE'] = data['BTCETH_PRICE'] * data['BTCETH_Units_Sold']
data['BTCETH_Value'] = data['BTCUSD_Value'] / data['BTCETH_PRICE']
###############################################################

### Sell ETHUSD from GDAX
# data['GBPUSD_Value'] = data['EURGBP_Value']*data['GBPUSD_Bid'] ### REFERENCE CODE 
#data['ETHUSD_Units_Sold'] = dollar_investment / data['ETHUSD_PRICE']
data['ETHUSD_Value'] = data['BTCETH_Value']*data['ETHUSD_PRICE'] 

### Calculate Arb Entry PRofit 
data['pre_profit'] = data['ETHUSD_Value'] - dollar_investment ## Reference code
